{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2018}} {{Infobox person |honorific_prefix = |name = Dennis Peron |honorific_suffix = |native_name = |native_name_lang = |image = Dennis Peron 2008 by Cary Newman.jpg |image_size = |caption = |birth_date = {{birth date|1945|04|08}} |birth_place = [[The Bronx]], [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S. |death_date = {{Death date and age|2018|01|27|1945|04|08}} |death_place = [[San Francisco, California]], U.S. |death_cause = |residence = San Francisco |nationality = [[Americans|American]] |years_active = 1970s–2018 |known_for = Activism for [[legality of cannabis|legalizing cannabis]]}}
'''Dennis Robert Peron''' (April 8, 1945<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sanfrancisco.cbslocal.com/2018/01/28/marijuana-trailblazer-dennis-peron-dies|title=Legal Marijuana Trailblazer Dennis Peron Dies at Age 72 in San Francisco|date=January 28, 2018|website=Sanfrancisco.cbslocal.com|accessdate=May 29, 2018}}</ref>&nbsp;– January 27, 2018) was an American [[Activism|activist]] and businessman who became a leader in the movement for the [[Legality of cannabis|legalization of cannabis]] throughout the 1990s. He influenced many in [[California]] and thus changed the [[Legal history of cannabis in the United States|political debate on marijuana in the United States]].<ref name="sfgate">{{citation|periodical=[[The San Francisco Examiner]]|url=https://www.sfgate.com/news/article/Long-rivalry-links-pot-raid-figures-3127435.php|title=Long rivalry links pot raid figures|author=Fernandez, Elizabeth|author2=Zamora, Jim Herron|date=August 18, 1996|accessdate=May 29, 2018}}</ref><ref name=Sandomir>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/30/obituaries/dennis-peron-early-medical-marijuana-advocate-dies-at-71.html|title=Dennis Peron, Early Medical Marijuana Advocate, Dies at 71|work=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|author=Sandomir, Richard|accessdate=May 29, 2018}}</ref>
==Biography== Peron was born in [[The Bronx]], [[New York City]], into an Italian-American family<ref name="IBT">{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/dennis-peron-cause-death-marijuana-activist-dies-71-2646402|title=Death: Marijuana Activist Dies At 71|date=January 28, 2018|author=L., Megha|publisher=International Business Times|accessdate=May 29, 2018}}</ref> and grew up in [[Long Island]]. He served in the [[United States Air Force]] in [[Vietnam]] during the [[Tet Offensive]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Downs, =David|url=http://blog.sfgate.com/smellthetruth/2014/11/11/why-you-can-thank-a-gay-hippie-vietnam-veteran-for-legal-medical-and-recreational-marijuana-today|title=Why you can thank a gay, hippie Vietnam veteran for legal medical and recreational marijuana today|website=SFGate|date=November 11, 2014|accessdate=May 29, 2018}}</ref> After the war, he moved to the [[Castro District, San Francisco]], where he became an active [[Youth International Party|Yippie]] and organized smoke-ins.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.sfgate.com/smellthetruth/2012/11/15/marijuana-legalization-seeds-planted-long-ago-finally-flower/|title=Marijuana Legalization: Seeds Planted Long Ago Finally Flower|website=SFGate|author=Oscar Pascual|access-date=November 15, 2012}}</ref><ref>[http://www.ibtimes.com/dennis-peron-cause-death-marijuana-activist-dies-71-2646402 Dennis Peron Cause of Death: Marijuana Activist Dies At 71], ibtimes.com; accessed May 29, 2018.</ref> He also supported gay activist [[Harvey Milk]], a former Long Island resident,<ref name="FL"/> who won an elected seat on the [[San Francisco Board of Supervisors]] in 1977.<ref name="IBT"/>
Peron sold [[cannabis]] from storefronts in the Castro and advocated for [[medical cannabis]], as he saw how patients with AIDS benefited from it. His partner, Jonathan West, whom he met in San Francisco, died of [[HIV/AIDS|AIDS]] in 1990.<ref name="IBT"/> In 1991, Peron organized for the passage of San Francisco's Proposition P, a resolution calling on the state government to permit medical cannabis, which received 79% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1996-12-01/news/mn-4581_1_dennis-peron|title=Force Behind Proposition 215 Says His Push Began as 'Legacy of Love'|author=Evans, Mark|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=December 1, 1996|accessdate=May 29, 2018}}</ref> That same year, he co-founded the [[San Francisco Cannabis Buyers Club]], the first public cannabis dispensary. His businesses were [[Police raid|raided]] by authorities in 1978 and 1990.<ref>{{cite web|author=Roberts, Chris|url=https://archives.sfweekly.com/sanfrancisco/news-marijuana-cannabis-sean-parker-auma-dennis-peron-prop-215-medical-marijuana-adult-use-of-marijuana-act/Content?oid=4434974|title=The Cannabis Legalizers Opposing Legalization|publisher=Archives.sfweekly.com|date=January 27, 2016|accessdate=May 29, 2018}}</ref> In 1993, Peron and [[Brownie Mary]] jointly released a cookbook with recipes for [[cannabis edible]]s.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/07/06/us/brownie-mary-fights-to-legalize-marijuana.html|title=Brownie Mary' Fights to Legalize Marijuana|first=Carey|last=Goldberg|work=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|date=July 6, 1996|accessdate=May 29, 2018}}</ref>
In 1996, Peron coauthored [[California Proposition 215 (1996)|California Proposition 215]], which sought to allow the use of medical cannabis.<ref name=obit/> [[Dan Lungren]], the [[Attorney General of California]], ordered a police raid of Peron's club a month before the election, arresting Peron.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1996-10-12/news/mn-53188_1_cannabis-buyers-club|title=Cannabis Buyers' Club Founder Arrested|work=Los Angeles Times|date=October 15, 1997|accessdate=May 29, 2018}}</ref> Proposition 215 was passed soon thereafter, which allowed the club to reopen. Later in 1996, the [[Grassroots-Legalize Cannabis Party]] of Minnesota fielded Peron as their nominee, their first, in the [[United States presidential election, 1996|U.S. presidential election]]. Peron received 5,400 votes.<ref name="BallotAccessNews1996presidentialvotes">{{cite news|author1=Bickford, Bob|author2=Ballot Access News|title=1996 Presidential Votes by State|date=October 7, 1998|url=http://www.ballot-access.org/1996/allvotes96.html}}</ref> In 1998, Peron ran in the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] primary for [[California]] governor against Lungren, who won the primary and lost the election to [[Gray Davis]].<ref name=ebar>{{cite web|author=Staver, Sari|url=http://www.ebar.com/news/article.php?sec=news&article=72343|title=SF honors Peron for medical cannabis work|publisher=Ebar.com|date=February 16, 2017|accessdate=May 29, 2018}}</ref>
Peron voiced support for [[Decriminalization of non-medical cannabis in the United States|decriminalization of all marijuana use]], believing that it is [[Medicine|medicinal]]. He opposed medical marijuana use for children.<ref>{{cite web|title=Medical Marijuana Policy in the United States|url=https://www.stanford.edu/group/hopes/cgi-bin/wordpress/2012/05/medical-marijuana-policy-in-the-united-states|publisher=Huntington's Outreach Project for Education, at Stanford|accessdate=May 29, 2018}}</ref> Peron opposed [[California Proposition 19 (2010)|California Proposition 19]] in 2010, which would have legalized recreational cannabis, because he did not believe that recreational use exists, as all people who use marijuana are using it medicinally.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://missionlocal.org/2010/09/local-marijuana-advocate-says-no-on-prop-19|title=Local Marijuana Advocate Says No on Prop. 19|publisher=MissionLocal|date=September 22, 2010|accessdate=May 29, 2018}}</ref> He opposed [[Adult Use of Marijuana Act|California Proposition 64]] in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/politics/la-pol-ca-proposition-64-recreational-pot-opponents-20161004-snap-story.html|title=The push to legalize pot for all has deeply divided the medical marijuana community|author=McGreevy, Patrick|website=Latimes.com|accessdate=May 29, 2018}}</ref>
Later in life, Peron owned and operated a {{convert|20|acre|adj=on}} cannabis farm near [[Clearlake, California]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfgate.com/news/article/Where-the-Grass-Is-Greener-Dennis-Peron-has-2948677.php|title=Where the Grass Is Greener/Dennis Peron has taken to growing and giving away marijuana on his farm|publisher=SFGate|date=February 5, 1999|accessdate=May 29, 2018}}</ref><ref name=Sandomir/> San Francisco's Board of Supervisors recognized Peron, who was suffering with late-stage lung cancer, with a certificate of honor in 2017.<ref name=obit/> Supervisor [[Jeff Sheehy]] called Peron "the father of medical cannabis".<ref name=ebar/> On January 27, 2018, aged 72,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2018/jan/28/dennis-peron-medical-marijuana-california-dies|title=Dennis Peron, father of medical marijuana in California, dies at 72|agency=[[Reuters]]|place=San Francisco|date=January 28, 2018|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]|accessdate=May 29, 2018}}</ref> Peron died of lung cancer at the [[San Francisco VA Medical Center|Veteran’s Administration Health Center]] in [[San Francisco]].<ref name="FL">{{cite web|url=https://www.freedomleaf.com/medical-marijuana-pioneer-dennis-peron/|title=California Medical-Marijuana Pioneer Dennis Peron Passes Away|publisher=FreedomLeaf|author=Bloom, Steve|date=January 27, 2018}}</ref><ref name=obit>{{cite web|author=Johnson, Lizzie|url=http://www.sfchronicle.com/bayarea/article/Dennis-Peron-called-father-of-medical-12531260.php|title=Dennis Peron, activist who helped legalize medical marijuana, dies|publisher=Sfchronicle.com|accessdate=May 29, 2018}}</ref>
